  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Specific legal definitions can vary by jurisdiction, but typically involve:\n\n1. Basic elements:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming criminal proceeds into seemingly legitimate money\n- Disguising the origin of financial assets\n\n2. Common legal components:\n- Intentional financial transactions\n- Knowing the funds derive from criminal activity\n- Attempting to make illegal money appear legitimate\n\n3. Key stages often include:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (conducting complex transactions to obscure origin)\n- Integration (reintroducing funds as seemingly legitimate)\n\n4. Jurisdictional variations exist, but most definitions require:\n- Intentional conduct\n- Knowledge of illegal source\n- Specific financial transactions\n\n5. Common predicate crimes include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Terrorism financing\n\nFor precise legal specifics, consulting local statutes and legal professionals is recommended, as definitions can differ significantly between countries and contexts.",
